Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta

Volume 185, 15 July 2016, Pages 278-301

Petrology and geochronology of lavas from Ka‘ula Volcano: Implications for rejuvenated volcanism of the Hawaiian mantle plume

Author links open overlay panel, , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gca.2016.03.025Get rights and content

Abstract

Marine surveying and submersible sampling of Ka‘ula Volcano, located 100 km off the axis of the Hawaiian chain, revealed widespread areas of young volcanism. New 40Ar/39Ar and geochemical analyses of the olivine-phyric submarine and subaerial volcanic rocks show that Ka‘ula is shrouded with 1.9–0.5 Ma alkalic basalts. The ages and chemistry of these rocks overlap with rejuvenated lavas on nearby, northern Hawaiian Island shields (Ni‘ihau, Kaua‘i and South Kaua‘i Swell). Collectively, these rejuvenated lavas cover a vast area (∼7000 km2), much more extensive than any other area of rejuvenated volcanism worldwide. Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas range widely in alkalinity and incompatible element abundances (e.g., up to 10× P2O5 at a given MgO value) and ratios indicating variable degrees of melting of a heterogeneous source. Heavy REE elements in Ka‘ula lavas are pinned at a mantle normalized Yb value of 10 ± 1, reflecting the presence of garnet in the source. Trace element ratios indicate the source also contained phlogopite and an Fe–Ti oxide. The new Ka‘ula ages show that rejuvenated volcanism was nearly coeval from ∼0.3 to 0.6 Ma along a 450 km segment of the Hawaiian Islands (from West Maui to north of Ka‘ula). The ages and volumes for rejuvenated volcanism are inconsistent with all but one geodynamic melting model proposed to date. This model advocates a significant contribution of pyroxenite to rejuvenated magmas. Analyses of olivine phenocryst compositions suggest a major (33–69%) pyroxenite component in Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas, which correlates positively with radiogenic Pb isotope ratios for Ka‘ula. This correlation is also observed in lavas from nearby South Kaua‘i lavas, as was reported for Atlantic oceanic islands. The presence of pyroxenite in the source may have extended the duration and volume of Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism.

1. Introduction

Mantle plumes are recognized by most geoscientists as the cause for mid-plate volcanism (e.g., Kerr, 2013). One intriguing but poorly understood aspect of mantle plumes is the resumption of volcanism hundreds of kilometers downstream from the ascending mantle plume stem following a hiatus in eruptive activity. This second period of volcanism is common on and around the shield volcanoes in many oceanic island groups including Samoa (Wright and White, 1987), Kerguelen (Weis et al., 1998), the Canary Islands (Hoernle and Schmincke, 1993), Madeira (Geldmacher and Hoernle, 2000), and Mauritius (Paul et al., 2005). Since its first recognition in Hawaii by Dana (1890), this second period of volcanism has been given many different names: post-erosional, rejuvenation, secondary, etc. Here we will use the common term “rejuvenation” to recognize the return of volcanism to the areas of previous shield activity. Volcanism on the flexural arch that surrounds the Hawaiian Islands is distinct because these areas are 200+ km off the axis of the hotspot trace and had no previous plume-related volcanism (e.g., Lipman et al., 1989, Frey et al., 2000). However, the major and trace element, and isotopic composition of arch lavas is very similar to rejuvenated lavas (e.g., Yang et al., 2003).

Comprehensive geochronological and magnetostratigraphy studies of other oceanic island such as Gran Canaria, an oceanic island in the Atlantic, have documented its episodic and protracted history of rejuvenated volcanism (∼5 Myr; Guillou et al., 2004). Although it has been argued that Gran Canaria’s long duration of rejuvenated volcanism is related to the slow movement of the African plate (1.9 cm/yr), its geologic history and rock compositions are very similar to those of Hawaiian and other oceanic islands and thus, probably share a similar origin (Carracedo et al., 1998).

Hawai‘i is the archetypal example of a plume-derived hotspot having produced the Hawaiian-Emperor Chain, one of the longest linear chains in time and space on Earth (e.g., Clague and Dalrymple, 1987, Garcia et al., 2015). Recent marine expeditions to the northern Hawaiian Islands (Garcia et al., 2008, Greene et al., 2010) and numerical modeling studies (Ballmer et al., 2011, Ballmer et al., 2013, Ballmer et al., 2015, Hofmann and Farnetani, 2013) have prompted renewed interest in the what, where, when and why of rejuvenated volcanism in the Hawaiian Islands. Our 2007 expedition surveyed and sampled Ka‘ula Volcano, which is located southwest of the islands of Kaua‘i and Ni‘ihau (Fig. 1). These surveys revealed extensive areas of rejuvenated submarine volcanism (Garcia et al., 2008). In this paper we present and interpret new compositional and geochronological data for submarine lavas lavas collected during two JASON dives on the NW and SE flanks of the volcano, and accidental volcanic blocks we collected from the tuff cone that caps the volcano.

2. Geologic setting and samples

Ka‘ula Island is a crescent shaped tuff cone remnant (∼0.5 km2) located ∼33 km west-southwest of the island of Niʻihau (Fig. 1), the oldest of the main Hawaiian Islands (Sherrod et al., 2007). The Ka‘ula tuff cone is located on the southeast corner of a wave-cut platform that caps a separate and distinct volcanic edifice unrelated to the nearby volcanic complexes that form the islands of Niʻihau and Kauaʻi (Hinds, 1930). These three complexes form a ridge that crosscuts the trend of the Hawaiian Islands with their volcanic centers spanning ∼130 km across the width of the Hawaiian plume, versus only ∼50 km for the southern Hawaiian Islands (Fig. 1). The origin of the anomalous Ka‘ula-Ni‘ihau-Kaua‘i (KNK) ridge has been related to a fracture in the underlying Cretaceous oceanic crust, possibly a splay of the Murray fracture zone (Macdonald et al., 1983). The KNK ridge is oriented roughly parallel to some of the factures and ridges in the Cretaceous oceanic crust west of the islands in the Kamehameha basin (Fig. 1). However, a synthesis map of the structure of the Cretaceous crust around the KNK ridge shows no major fractures disrupting the abyssal hill fabric or magnetic anomalies east or west of the ridge that align with its trend (e.g., Holcomb and Robinson, 2004). The absence of a structural weakness in the surrounding oceanic crust leaves open the question of the origin of this anomalous cross-trend ridge. Another cross-trend ridge with three volcanic complexes has been proposed for Moloka‘i Island area, ∼200 km to the south (Xu et al., 2014). No explanation has been given for its origin.

Ka‘ula Volcano has been poorly studied because of its remote location (Fig. 1) and use as a bombing target by the U.S. military since World War II. The volcano was not mentioned in the recent compilation of the geology of the State of Hawai‘i (Sherrod et al., 2007). The first preliminary description of Ka‘ula’s geology was by Palmer (1927). The petrology and age of some lithic volcanic blocks from the island (tholeiite, phonolite, alkalic basalt and basanite) were documented by Garcia et al. (1986). Eight of these samples (a tholeiite, alkalic basalt and six basanites) are included in our study. Numerous garnet pyroxenite and spinel peridotite lithic blocks are also present on the island (Garcia and Presti, 1987). Isotope (Hf, Nd, Sr, Pb) analyses of a few basanite, phonolite and pyroxenite xenoliths were presented by Bizimis et al. (2013) on samples from the Garcia et al. (1986) and Presti (1982) studies. Three of these basanites are included in our study (KA-19, -28, -34). The Ka‘ula phonolites have been well documented (Garcia et al., 1986, Bizimis et al., 2013) and are not discussed in this paper.

Eighty-one new lava samples were colllected during two JASON remotely operated vehicle dives on opposite sides of the main Ka‘ula edifice (Fig. 2). Dive 300 traversed a field of flat-topped cones on Ka‘ula’s northwest apron collecting multiple basaltic samples from six cones at depths of 3927–3125 mbsl before ascending the northwest flank of the main edifice and recovering samples from a broad terrace and nearby ridge to 2530 mbsl. Dive 304 sampled two terraces on the lower southeast flank of the Ka‘ula submarine edifice starting at 3615 mbsl, then sampled a pointed cone between 2607 and 2411 mbsl (cone F) before ascending and collecting samples along a ridge (that may have been one of Ka‘ula’s rift zones) to 1700 mbsl (Fig. 2). Forty-four pillow basalts were collected on dive 300 and 37 during dive 304 (Table S1).

3. Analytical techniques

The 40Ar/39Ar ages were determined in two labs. Seven submarine samples were analyzed at Oregon State University using methods described by Koopers et al. (2003) and Duncan and Keller (2004). These samples maximize the geographic coverage, have higher K2O contents (0.49–1.43 wt.%), and are the freshest (based on petrography and lower loss-on-igniton, LOI; <0.95 wt.%) for the submarine suite. Holocrystalline matrix material from the interior of the pillow basalts was finely crushed (<1 mm) with a tungsten-carbide (WC) coated hydraulic press, ultrasonically cleaned in Millipore water and dried for 24 h at 40 °C. Dried crushed rock was sieved to 250–350 μm. Phenocrysts were removed from the sieved split using a Frantz magnetic barrier separator and/or heavy liquids. Groundmass separates were hand picked under a binocular microscope to avoid grains with secondary alteration. Two subaerial samples (KA-14 and -31) were prepared using the same handling methods and analyzed at the University of Wisconsin at Madison using procedures described in Jicha et al. (2012).

Microprobe analyses were made of glass and olivine in Ka‘ula samples using the University of Hawai‘i five-spectrometer, JEOL HyperProbe. Glasses were analyzed from all glass-bearing submarine samples (31 from dive 300 and 23 from dive 304). Major element and S analyses of glass were obtained with a 15 kV accelerating voltage, 10 nA beam current and a 10 mm diameter beam. The reported analyses are an average of 10 spot analyses per sample. Accuracy and precision are estimated at <1% for major elements and 2–5% for minor elements (<1 wt.%) based on repeat analyses of a Hawaiian glass standard (A99) and Juan de Fuca glass (VG-2) from the Smithsonian collection (e.g., Jarosewich et al., 1979). Olivine was analysed using higher precision methods; 20 kV, 200 nA and longer counting times (Si, Mg, Ni, Ca, 115 s on peak, 90 s total on background for each element; Mn, 75 s on peak, 60 s on background; Fe, 30 s on peak, 30 s on background). Larger crystals were used for Fe, Mn (LIFH) and Ca (PETH) to obtain higher count rates. The standards used for calibration were San Carlos olivine USNM 111312/444 (SiO2, MgO, FeO; Jarosewich et al., 1980), synthetic Mn-olivine (MnO; Shannon et al., 1991), UCLA Diopside (CaO), and synthetic Ni-olivine (Ito, 1975). Raw X-ray intensities were converted into weight percent via ZAF correction methods (Armstrong, 1988). Two sigma errors are <0.03 wt.% for SiO2, MgO and FeO and <0.01 wt.% for CaO, MnO and NiO based on 10 replicate analyses of the San Carlos olivine standard.

A subset of volcanic rock samples was analyzed by XRF (25 from dive 300 and 30 from dive 304) to provide geographic and rock type (based on petrography glass analyses) coverage. Samples were coarsely crushed (1–8 mm) with a tungsten-carbide (WC) coated hydraulic press, ultrasonically cleaned in Millipore water, dried for 24 h at 40 °C, and hand-picked to remove fragments with signs of alteration. This procedure ensured that only the freshest parts of each sample were analyzed. The efficiency of this process is reflected by the relatively low loss-on-ignition (LOI) values (for methods, see Rhodes, 1996) for most samples (<1.0 wt.%). The clean rock fragments were split into two aliquots; one for XRF and the other for ICP-MS analyses. Samples for XRF analysis were powdered using WC-lined mills, and analyzed for major and trace elements at the University of Massachusetts (for analytical procedures and precision see Rhodes and Vollinger, 2004).

Twenty of the freshest (i.e., low LOI) submarine samples (ten from each dive) and two accidental blocks from the island (tholeiite KA-14 and basanite KA-31) were selected for trace element analyses by HR-ICP-MS on a Thermo Finnigan Element2 at the Pacific Centre for Isotopic and Geochemical Research (PCIGR) at the University of British Columbia. Samples were powdered in an agate mill, digested in concentrated sub-boiled HF and HNO3 for 48 h, and then redigested in 6 N sub-boiled HCl for 24 h. Once dried, they were redissolved in concentrated HNO3, dried down again and diluted 5000 times using a 10 ppb in, 1% HNO3 solution. For a detailed description of the trace element analysis procedures, see Carpentier et al. (2013) and Schudel et al. (2015).

4. Results

4.1. 40Ar/39Ar dating

Previous age determinations of Ka‘ula lavas were performed using conventional K-Ar methods on two phonolites and an alkalic basalt collected from the tuff cone (Garcia et al., 1986). The phonolites yielded whole-rock ages of 4.01 ± 0.09 and 4.22 ± 0.25 Ma. A biotite separate from the 4.2 Ma phonolite yielded an age of 3.98 ± 0.70 Ma. The strongly evolved alkalic composition and intermediate age of the phonolites were interpreted as representing Ka‘ula’s post-shield stage of volcanism (Garcia et al., 1986). The alkalic basalt gave an age of 1.8 ± 0.2 Ma, which was thought to reflect Ka‘ula’s rejuvenated stage of volcanism based on the age and compositional similarities to rejuvenated lavas from nearby Niʻihau and Kauaʻi islands (Garcia et al., 1986).

New work on seven Ka‘ula submarine alkali basalts yielded plateau ages of 0.55–1.95 Ma with all plateaus having a high percentage of 39Ar released (88–100%, most >96%), low MSWD values (0.02 and 0.15, most <0.10) and 40Ar/36Ar intercepts overlaping the atmospheric value (Tables 1 and S2). Thus, the plateau ages are used here as the preferred ages for the Ka‘ula lavas (Table 1). The ages for four dive 304 samples decrease along the uphill dive traverse from 1.24 to 0.55 Ma. The oldest age for a submarine sample (300-10, 1.95 ± 0.19 Ma) was from a cone with the most sediment cover based on dive observations and sidescan sonar images. Samples from two other cones with less sediment cover were collected on dive 300; they gave younger ages (0.81 ± 0.56 and 0.92 ± 0.57 Ma). A basanite accidental block from the island (KA-31) gave a plateau age of 0.663 ± 0.085 Ma (Tables 1 and S3).

The range of ages for alkalic Ka‘ula rocks (0.55–1.95 Ma) overlaps with the K-Ar ages for rejuvenated lavas from Ni‘ihau (0.35–2.68 Ma; Sherrod et al., 2007), Kaua‘i (0.15–2.52 Ma; Garcia et al., 2010), West Ka‘ena (0.36–1.47 Ma; Greene et al., 2010) and South Kaua‘i Swell areas (0.1–1.9 Ma; Garcia et al., 2015). The similar ages (Fig. 3) and compositions (alkalic basalt to foidite) between the lavas from these nearby centers strongly suggest that the Ka‘ula lavas are from a rejuvenated stage of volcanism.

A tholeiitic block (KA-14) from the island yielded a 40Ar/39Ar plateau age of 6.24 ± 0.08 Ma (Tables 1 and S3). This age, the oldest from the Hawaiian Islands with an error of less than 1 Myr (Sherrod et al., 2007), and its tholeiitic composition (Garcia et al., 1986) are indicative that the sample is from Ka‘ula’s shield stage (Fig. 3).

4.2. Petrography

The suite of submarine Ka‘ula rocks share many common petrographic features: most have an unaltered glassy or cyptocrystalline matrix, are weakly vesicular (<5 vol.%; Table S4) and olivine phyric (>5 vol.% total olivine phenocrysts, >0.5 mm wide, and microphenocrysts, 0.1–0.5 mm wide) with a median value of 8 vol.% (Tables S4). About a third of the samples are picritic with 10–18 vol.% olivine (Table S4). Many of the dive 304 samples also contain rare (<2 vol.%) microphenocrysts of plagioclase. Plagioclase is less abundant in samples from dive 300 (20% of samples vs. 35% in dive 304 samples, although sample 300–10 contains ∼4 vol.% plagioclase; Table S4). A few samples (collected on the shallower, <2700 m, flanks of the submarine edifice) have clinopyroxene microphenocryts. Typically, samples with clinopyroxene microphenocrysts lack plagioclase microphenocrysts. The uncommon occurrence of clinopyroxene in Ka‘ula samples is striking compared to rejuvenated lavas from Honolulu (Winchell, 1947) but is similar to the weakly alkaline lavas from Kaua‘i (Garcia et al., 2010). Minor alteration is evident in a few Ka‘ula samples (thin rim of palagonite rim on glass, 1–2 mm thick and/or clay lining some vesicles) under typically a thin (<1–3 mm) Mn coating.

The basaltic blocks from Ka‘ula Island range widely in mineralogy. Olivine is ubiquitous; most of the samples contain 6–11 vol.% total olivine, whereas the tholeiite (KA-14) and an alkaline basalt (KA-29) have <2 vol.% olivine and plagioclase microphenocrysts, which are absent in the other samples. These non-plagioclase bearing samples contain clinopyroxene as phenocrysts, microphenocrysts and/or xenocrysts (e.g., sample KA-15 has abundant cpx xenocrysts, 17 vol.%; Table S4). All of the volcanic blocks are moderately to strongly vesicular (19–70 vol.%) except sample KA-34 (7 vol.%; Table S4). Zeolites (mainly phillipsite and natrolite) are present in the vesicles of the blocks) and rare calcite was found in sample KA-34 but is absent in all other samples.

4.3. Olivine chemistry

Olivine core compositions were determined for six submarine (dive 304) and four subaerial basalts from Ka‘ula Volcano. These samples were chosen to span a wide range in composition and for the presence of fresh olivine phenocrysts; all are from the rejuvenation stage. Olivine from these basalts show a broad range in forsterite content (Fo; 82.0–91.0; Table 2). The subaerial samples KA-19, -31 and -34 contain olivine with the highest Fo values (89–91%). These crystals have low CaO contents (0.02–0.09 wt.%; Table 2) but are euhedral. Such low CaO values are generally considered to be indicative of mantle-derived olivine (e.g., SØager et al., 2015). In backscatter images, these crystals are strongly zoned with a round Mg-rich core. These subaerial lavas also contain anhedral olivine with low CaO contents, which we consider to be xenocrysts. Thus, the low CaO olivines are also probably xenocrysts that were mantle derived and subsequently overgrown with moderate forsterite olivine (Fo 85–88). The olivine with moderate CaO contents span a wider Fo range for the subaerial samples than the submarine samples (3–7% vs. 1–3%; except sample 304–23; Fig. 4). Most of the olivine in four of the submarine samples plot within the equilibrium field (Fig. 4) suggesting these basalts are representative of magmatic compositions (e.g., did not accumulate olivine phenocrysts or antecrysts). Olivine that plots above the equilibrium field (Fig. 4) from the submarine and subaerial samples are probably either xenocrysts (low CaO) or antecrysts.

4.4. Glass chemistry

Pillow rim glasses were analyzed for major elements and S in 54 Ka‘ula submarine lavas (not all samples had glass). The glasses all have weakly alkalic basalt compositions with moderate contents of SiO2 (45.6–48.0 wt.%) and total alkalis (3.2–4.7 wt.%; Table 3). The glasses range in MgO content from 6.0 to 8.4 wt.% and have a wide range in K2O (0.35–1.04 wt.%; Fig. 5). Glasses from the dives on opposite sides of Ka‘ula are somewhat chemically distinct (e.g., separate trends on MgO vs. K2O and Al2O3 plots; Fig. 5). Dive 304 glasses have higher K2O and Al2O3 than those from dive 300 (Fig. 5), and also higher Na2O and P2O5 (Table 3). Divergent CaO/Al2O3 trends with decreasing MgO are present for dive 304 glasses (Fig. 5). Glasses on the increasing CaO/Al2O3 trend have higher CaO contents than those on the decreasing trend at similar MgO contents (12.8–13.0 wt.% vs. ⩽12.1 wt.%; Table 3). The glasses from the decreasing trend are from the shallowest areas sampled (Table 3). Ka‘ula glasses have higher K2O and CaO/Al2O3 at a given MgO compared to submarine glasses from rejuvenated lavas of nearby Ni‘ihau (Fig. 5) indicating distinct parental magma compositions for the two volcanic regions. These chemical differences may allow the distribution of the lavas from these two adjacent and overlapping volcanic fields on the north sides of Ka‘ula and Ni‘ihau islands (Fig. 2) to be delineated in future sampling.

The sulfur content of Ka‘ula submarine glasses ranges from 0.10 to 0.19 wt.% (Table 3). All of the glasses collected at depths >2500 m contain ⩾0.140 wt.% S, indicating they were probably undegassed (Fig. 5). These glasses are also weakly vesicular (⩽4 vol.%; Table S2). More vesicular samples (>10 vol.%) typically had no glass or have lower S contents (0.10–.012 wt.% S; Table 3). These lower S glasses were collected on dive 304 from shallower water depths, <2400 m, along the southeast ridge. Two positive trends are evident in the S vs. depth data for dive 304 glasses; one for ridge samples and the other for cone F (Fig. 5). No correlation was found for S with FeO content (which has been observed in some suites of mid-ocean ridge glasses; e.g., Mathez, 1976), although S content generally increases with decreasing MgO for dive 300 glasses (Table 3). Ni‘ihau submarine glasses have similar to somewhat lower S contents (0.06–0.19 wt.%; Dixon et al., 2008) than Ka‘ula glasses (median values, 0.12 vs. 0.15 wt.%, respectively). The lower value for some Ni‘ihau glasses probably reflects their somewhat shallower water depth of collection (∼1000 m; Dixon et al., 2008).

4.5. Whole-rock major elements

Sixty-four Ka‘ula samples were analyzed by XRF for major elements; eight from the island, 25 from dive 300 and 31 from dive 304 (Table 4). All of these Ka‘ula volcanic rocks are alkalic except a tholeiitic volcanic lithic block from the island, sample KA-14 (Fig. 6). SiO2 contents for the alkalic rocks range from 40.9 to 47.8 wt.% and total alkalis from 2.9 to 5.4 wt.% making the Ka‘ula lavas foiditic to weakly alkalic basalts (Fig. 6). The volcanic blocks from the island show the greatest variation in SiO2 and total alkalis (Fig. 6). Samples from dive 300 are somewhat less alkali-rich than those from dive 304 (Table 4). The alkalic compositions and the ages of the dated samples (0.55–1.95 Ma; Table 1) are typical of Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism in the northern Hawaiian Islands (Fig. 3, Fig. 6).

The MgO contents for Ka‘ula lavas vary from 6.2 to 13.4 wt.% with a positive but scattered correlation with total olivine content (Table S4). The median MgO content is relatively high (∼11 wt.%), which is typical for Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (e.g., Winchell, 1947). The P2O5 content of Ka‘ula rocks at the same MgO is remarkably variable (0.2–1.1 wt.%; Fig. 7). Many of the samples from both dives show a relatively tight, increasing trend for P2O5 with decreasing MgO. The volcanic blocks from the island show the widest variability in P2O5 at a given MgO content (Fig. 7). A wide range in CaO/Al2O3 values is also seen for Ka‘ula rocks with no apparent decrease at lower MgO values (<7 wt.%; Fig. 7). This suggests that neither plagioclase nor clinopyroxene fractionation was significant in the more evolved Ka‘ula rocks, which is consistent with scarcity of these minerals in Ka‘ula rocks (Table S4). There is a wide range in CaO/Al2O3 and P2O5 at higher MgO values (⩾10 wt.%; Fig. 7) indicating a diversity in parental magma compositions.

Ka‘ula samples generaly have higher total alkali, and lower SiO2 contents and higher P2O5 at a given MgO compared to rejuvenated submarine lavas from nearby Ni‘ihau (Fig. 6, Fig. 7). However, the Ka’ula rocks overlap in composition with rejuvenated lavas from the Honolulu series and Kaua‘i (not shown), although these other two groups extend to lower SiO2 (36 wt.%) and higher P2O5 (1.5 wt.%; Clague and Frey, 1982, Garcia et al., 2010) than Ka‘ula lavas.

4.6. Trace elements

4.6.1. XRF results

Trace elements were analyzed by XRF for the same 64 Ka‘ula samples analyzed for major elements (Table 4). Alteration is known to play an important role in modifying the composition of Hawaiian basalts (Frey and Rhodes, 1993). Thus, the effects of alteration on the abundance of these elements need to be identified before attempting to evaluate possible magmatic causes for trace element variations. The abundance of Rb and K are highly succeptible to modification in subaerial Hawaiian lavas, which leads to high and variable K/Rb values (e.g., Feigenson, 1984, Frey and Rhodes, 1993). The K/Rb ratio in Ka‘ula lavas is nearly constant (R2 = 0.93 for all samples; Fig. 8), which is remarkable given the wide variations in major element contents (Fig. 5, Fig. 6, Fig. 7). If the island samples are excluded because of the presence of secondary minerals (Table S4), the R2 for K/Rb improves to 0.95. One of the island samples, KA-19, has extremely high Sr content (6400 ppm; Fig. 9). This sample is highly vesicular (∼70 vol.%) with abundant zeolites. Zeolites in volcanic rocks can contain substantial Sr (e.g., Cappelletti et al., 2011). The composition of the vesicle-filling minerals in sample KA-19 by energy dispersive analysis (EDS). Some but not all of the zeolites in this sample have 0.7–3.3 wt.% SrO (Table S5; Fig. A.1). These zeolites also contain up to 2 wt.% BaO, although the BaO and SrO contents are not well correlated (Table S5). Backscatter imagery revealed a high atomic number mineral in a few vesicles and irregular voids (Fig. A.1). EDS scans showed the mineral is Sr- and S-rich (celestite; Fig. A.1), which has not been reported previously in Hawaiian basalts. Celestite in volcanic rocks is typically found in hydrothermal veins (e.g., Deer et al., 2013). This presence of celestite at Ka‘ula is probably related to hydrothermal activity in the shallow volcanic edifice under the island. Alteration is not the likely cause of elevated Sr (>1100 ppm) in five submarine samples (300–38, 304–20 to 23; Fig. 9; Table 4). These samples also have at least triple the abundance of incompatible elements compared to the other submarine samples (Table 4), are strongly vesicular (18–40 vol.%; Table S4) compared to other submarine Ka‘ula samples (median of 0.7 vol.%) and only weakly altered with no apparent secondary minerals. Thus, their high incompatible element content is a primary feature, as observed in other Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (e.g., Clague and Frey, 1982, Yang et al., 2003, Dixon et al., 2008, Garcia et al., 2010).

Abundances of compatible trace elements Ni and Cr are relatively high in Ka‘ula rejuvenated volcanic rocks (median values of 262 and 452 ppm, respectively) reflecting the comparatively high median MgO content of these rocks (∼11 wt.%; Table 4). Elements that are typically highly incompatible in alkaline basalts (Rb, Nb and Ba) have wide ranges (5–7× variation) at a given MgO value (Table 4). Samples from dives 300 and 304 show multiple, coherent trends for Nb (Fig. 9) and other incompatible elements (Table 4) as observed for major elements (Fig. 5, Fig. 7). The well defined trends for major and trace elements, and wide range in Nb concentrations at 10 wt.% MgO (Fig. 8) indicate Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas had a diversity of parental magma compositions. Honolulu rejuvenated lavas also show the same highly incompatible element variability, which was attributed to 5x range in partial melting of a homogeneous source (Clague and Frey, 1982). Subsequent studies of Os Sr and Pb isotopes in the Honolulu lavas have shown the source to be somewhat heterogeneous (e.g., Lassiter et al., 2000, Yang et al., 2003, Fekiakova et al., 2007).

A plot of Zr/Y vs. Nb/Y (Fitton, 2007) is useful for discriminating lavas from the various stages of Hawaiian volcanism including alkaline rocks from the post-shield vs. rejuvenated stages (Yang et al., 2003). Ka‘ula alkaline rocks plot near the upper limit of the Icelandic OIB field and within but near the base of the field for Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (Fig. 8). The Ka‘ula tholeiite (KA-14) plots in the Hawaiian shield lava field (Fig. 8). These stage designations support the interpretations presented above based on age and other geochemical results for these Ka‘ula samples.

4.6.2. ICP-MS results

Twenty-two of the 64 samples analyzed by XRF were analyzed by HR-ICP-MS for trace element concentations (Table 5). The 22 samples were selected to span the geochemical variation observed in the XRF results, cover a wide area of the volcano and for their low level of alteration based on petrography and LOI values (Tables S4 and 4). Reference materials USFGS, BHVO-2 and Kil93 were also analysed and the values obtained are within 2σ error of recommended values (Table 5). Duplicates and replicate measurements show excellent agreement, with relative standard deviations (RSD) less than 3% for most elements. Procedural blank values for the rare earth elements (REE) and most other elements are in the ppt range, and are considered negligible in comparison to the sample concentrations, which are in the ppm range. Values obtained for incompatible elements (e.g., Rb, Ba Nb, Zr and Sr) that were analyzed by both XRF and ICP-MS methods are in excellent agreement (R2 > 0.985).

Values of Sc are relatively high (median value 28.7 ppm) in Ka‘ula submarine lavas but unlike the other normally compatible elements in basalts (Cr and Ni), they increase somewhat with decreasing MgO (Table 4, Table 5). These results confirm petrographic observations that clinopyroxene fractionation (DSc = ∼ 2.5; Norman et al., 2005) did not play an important role in the magmatic history of the Ka‘ula rocks. Likewise, the absence of a Eu anomaly in Ka‘ula lavas (Fig. 10) is consistent with other geochemical and petrographic evidence that plagioclase did not significantly affect the composition of these lavas.

The REE patterns for all Ka‘ula volcanic rocks are remarkably similar including the tholeiite, KA-14, even when plotted on a linear rather than log scale (Fig. 10). Nearly all of the REE patterns are pinned at the same chondrite-normalized, heavy REE values (e.g., Ybn 10 ± 1; Fig. 10) and fan out broadly in light REE (Fig. 10, Table 5). Two samples (300-10 and -38) have somewhat higher heavy REE values (Ybn = 18) and steeper light to middle REE patterns (Fig. 10; Table 4). The wide variation in light REE concentrations for Ka‘ula lavas (chondrite normalized values, Lan from 38 to 261; Fig. 10) is much greater than observed for rejuvenated lavas from nearby Ni‘ihau (33–71, median 50; Dixon et al., 2008). The Lan range for Ka‘ula lavas is comparable to that observed for Kaua‘i rejuvenated lavas, although Ka‘ula rocks extend to lower values (Kaua‘i, Lan = 105–291; Garcia et al., 2010). No crossing REE patterns were found for Ka‘ula alkalic lavas, unlike patterns for other suites of Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (e.g., Ni‘ihau, Kaua‘i and Honolulu; Yang et al., 2003, Garcia et al., 2010, Cousens and Clague, 2015) and those from Mauritius in the Indian Ocean (Moore et al., 2011). Another major distinction between Ka‘ula and Mauritius lavas is the lack of variation in heavy REEs for Ka‘ula rocks.

Other incompatible elements range greatly in Ka‘ula rejuvenated rocks (e.g., Pb – 0.5–60 ppm; Table 5). The two samples with the highest Pb concentrations (58 and 60 ppm) are the ones with higher REE (300-10 and -38). Two other Ka‘ula rocks also have Pb values >7 ppm (Table 5), which is higher than any other Hawaiian Island rejuvenated lavas (Ni‘ihau, 0.5–1.6 ppm, Dixon et al., 2008; Kaua‘i, 1.2–3.5, Cousens and Clague, 2015; Honolulu, 1.3–6.9, Yang et al., 2003). The two samples with the highest Pb and REE concentrations are also enriched in other incompatible elements (e.g., Th, U, Li) as well as Cd, Zn, Sb, W, Bi, Mo and Y (Table 5). As noted above, these rocks are unaltered or only weakly altered (minor iddingsite with no other secondary minerals). Thus, the high incompatible element content of some Ka‘ula samples is probably a source feature.

On a primitive mantle normalized diagram, Ka‘ula alkalic rocks have positive anomalies for Ba and Sr, and negative anomalies for Cs, Rb, Th, U, Pb, Zr and Hf (Fig. 11, plotted on a linear scale), which yields high Ba/Th and Sr/Nd and low Zr/Sm ratios. Unusually wide ranges are observed for some elements on this diagram (Ba, Pb, light REE and Sr) creating crossing patterns (Fig. 12). Similar patterns are found for rejuvenated lavas from Honolulu, Kaua‘i and Ni‘ihau (e.g., Yang et al., 2003, Dixon et al., 2008, Garcia et al., 2010, Cousens and Clague, 2015) as well as those from Mauritius (Moore et al., 2011). The wide variations in Pb and Sr concentrations in Mauritius lavas has been attributed to the mobility of these elements in groundwater (Moore et al., 2011). This explanation is not valid for the submarine lavas collected from uneroded flanks of Ka‘ula. Thus variations in Pb and Sr concentrations at Ka‘ula and other oceanic islands may be a primary feature of some rejuvenated lavas.

5. Discussion

5.1. Source mineralogy and heterogeneity

High-pressure melting experiments on dry peridotite have been unable to produce reasonable parent melt compositions for ocean island alkaline basalts (e.g., Walter, 1998). One possible way to produce alkaline melts from a peridotite source is with the presence of a hydrous phase (phlogopite or amphibole; e.g., Pilet et al., 2008). Key elements for identifying the presence and type of a hydrous phase are Rb, Ba and K. Partition coefficient (KD) values for these elements in an alkaline basalt are distinctly higher for phlogopite 2.5–3.7 compared to amphibole (0.2–0.6; LaTourrette et al., 1995). Generally, these elements are mobile during even low temperature alteration in subaerial Hawaiian lavas leading to high and variable K/Rb values (e.g., Feigenson, 1984, Frey and Rhodes, 1993). However, Ka‘ula lavas, especially the submarine suite, show nearly constant K/Rb and Nb/Ba ratios (R2 = 0.93 and 0.96, respectively, for all samples; Fig. 8). Thus, abundances of these elements as well as other less mobile incompatible elements are useful for determining the source mineralogy and heterogeneity for Ka‘ula lavas.

The source for Ka‘ula lavas probably contained residual phologopite and Ti-oxide. Ratios of K/Ce, Rb/La and Ba/La show a factor of 2–3 variation and broad negative correlations (R2 = ∼0.6) when plotted against a highly incompatible element (Nb), especially for the dive 300 samples (Fig. 12 and Table 5). These features are consistent with the control of residual phlogopite for Ka‘ula lavas (e.g., LaTourrette et al., 1995, Class and Goldstein, 1997). Amphibole in the source would not have sufficient leverage on K, Rb and Ba to counteract the effects of very low KD for these elements in other source minerals (olivine and pyroxene; e.g., Yang et al., 2003). Also, amphibole is unlikely to be present in the Hawaiian mantle plume given its shallow stability for an oceanic geotherm (<3 GPa; Foley, 1991) compared to the probable depth of magma generation in the Hawaiian mantle plume (>3 GPa; e.g., Hofmann and Farnetani, 2013). Ka‘ula lavas show depletions in Zr and Hf on a mantle-normalized diagram (Fig. 11), a positive trend of Zr/Hf vs. Nb (i.e., high ratios at low degrees of partial melting; Fig. 12) and relatively low TiO2 contents compared to most alkaline oceanic island lavas (∼1 wt.% lower at the same SiO2 and 2 wt.% lower than melts produced from amphibole-bearing peridotite; Pilet et al., 2008). Honolulu lavas show similar major and trace element characteristics, which were interpreted to indicate residual Ti-oxide in their source during melting (Yang et al., 2003).

Residual garnet in the source for the Ka‘ula rocks is indicated by the nearly complete lack of variation in heavy REE concentration despite the wide range in the LREE (Fig. 10; e.g., Lanphere and Frey, 1987). The presence of garnet in the mantle source for Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas is also likely the cause of the correlation of Tb/Yb vs. Th and low Sc values (e.g., Clague et al., 2016). Ka‘ula lavas show a good correlation of Tb/Yb vs. Th (R2 = 0.88; Fig. 13) except for two samples (300-10, -38) with anomalously high heavy REE and other highly incompatible elements (Table 5; Fig. 11). These samples must have been derived from a distinct source. Most Honolulu rejuvenated lavas also have a good correlation for Tb/Yb vs. Th, which was interpreted to indicate the presence of garnet in their source (Yang et al., 2003). Compared to Honolulu lavas, Ka‘ula samples have overlapping but generally lower Tb/Yb values (0.31–0.65 vs. 0.5–1.35) and Th contents (0.6–6.2 vs. 1.9–12.0; Table 3; Yang et al., 2003). The variation in Th content of Honolulu lavas was interpreted to reflect varing degrees of partial melting (Clague and Frey, 1982, Yang et al., 2003). Thus, the lower Tb/Yb values in Ka‘ula lavas probably reflects a higher degree of melting in these rocks compared to those from Honolulu.

Ka‘ula lavas show a wide range in abundances of incompatible elements at constant MgO content (up to 10x for P2O5 and Th; Fig. 7; Table 3, Table 5). Honolulu rejuvenated lavas also have large variations in highly incompatible elements, which were attributed to variations in the degree of melting of a homogeneous source (e.g., Clague and Frey, 1982). Ka‘ula lavas undoubtedly experienced variable degrees of partially melting based on the variations in their alkalinity index (total alkalis – (SiO2 * 0.37–14.43); Rhodes and Vollinger, 2004) of 0.1 to 4.2 (see also Fig. 6) and the 5x variation in ratios of highly over moderately compatible elements (e.g., La/Yb; Fig. 12). Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas were probably also derived from a heterogeneous source based on the large range in ratios of highly incompatible elements (e.g., 4× for Ba/Th; Fig. 13). This is consistent with recent studies of Honolulu lavas that showed these lavas are heterogeneous, espeically for Os and to a lesser extent for Pb and Sr isotopes (e.g., Lassiter et al., 2000, Yang et al., 2003, Fekiakova et al., 2007).

Two dominant source components are evident for Ka‘ula submarine lavas based on the correlation of highly incompatible trace element ratios (e.g., R2 = 0.69 for Ba/Th vs. Nb/La for all samples and 0.91 for the 10 dive 300 lavas; Fig. 13). The good postive correlation for dive 300 samples (which includes the two with anomalously high heavy REE and other highly incompatible elements on most plots; Fig. 8, Fig. 12, Fig. 13) is indicative of a partial melting trend (e.g., Dixon et al., 2008). In contrast, submarine rejuvenated lavas from Ni‘ihau show a negative correlation on the Ba/Th vs. Nb/La plot (Fig. 13), which was interpreted to reflect the addition of up to 0.2% carbonatite melt to a peridotite source (Dixon et al., 2008). Presence of even minor amounts of carbonatite in periodotitic source would enhance the generation of alkaline melts (e.g., Dasgupta and Hirschmann, 2007). However, the lack of a negative trend on this plot for Ka‘ula lavas and all other Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (Yang et al., 2003, Garcia et al., 2010, Garcia et al., 2015, Greene et al., 2010) except those from Ni‘ihau (Dixon et al., 2008) requires an alternative explanation for the enrichment of trace elements in rejuvenated vs. shield lavas.

Metasomatism has been invoked to explain the dichotomy of high concentrations of strongly incompatible elements but depleted ratios of Nd and Sr isotopes in Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas (e.g., Class and Goldstein, 1997, Roden et al., 1984, Yang et al., 2003). Recycled oceanic crust is commonly utilized as a source component for producing alkaline magmas (e.g., Hofmann, 1997). One mechanism for metasomatism is veining of amphibole of the upper mantle, which has been observed in some peridotite massifs (Pilet et al., 2008). Amphibole-bearing xenoliths and even hornblendite have been recovered as accidental blocks from Salt Lake Crater within the Honolulu Volcanics (Sen et al., 1996). The reaction of melts derived from amphibole-rich veins with surrounding lherzolite can explain observed compositional trends for some oceanic island suites of nephelinite to alkali olivine basalts (Pilet et al., 2008). However, Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas are too poor in TiO2 (1.2–2.8 wt.%, increasing with alkalinity; Table 3) compared to the liquids produced from the amphibole-peridotite melting experiments (3.5–5.5 wt.%; Pilet et al., 2008). Thus, an alternative metasomatic component is needed. As discussed below, the additional component that may be responsible for the extended duration and high volume of rejuvenated volcanism in the northern Hawaiian Islands is pyroxenite.

5.2. Implications of ages and aerial extent for origin of Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism

The mechanism responsible for generating rejuvenated volcanism remains controversial (e.g., Hofmann and Farnetani, 2013). Several models have been proposed for rejuvenated volcanism, including upwelling away from the rising stem of the plume (Ribe and Christensen, 1999, Hofmann and Farnetani, 2013) and flexure- induced decompressional melting related to loading or trench bending (Bianco et al., 2005, Konter and Jackson, 2012). Any viable model must explain the apparent decrease in the time gap between the end of the shield volcanism and the onset of rejuvenation (0.6–2 Myr; Ozawa et al., 2005) with distance towards Kīlauea, the long duration of rejuvenated volcanism on some shield volcanoes (1–2.65 Myr; Fig. 3) and the large volumes of rejuvenated lavas on at least some shields (e.g., 58 km3; Kaua‘i; Garcia et al., 2010). There are insufficient stratigraphic data for most areas of rejuvenated volcanism in Hawaii (and elsewhere around the world) to estimate the volumes of lavas erupted, especially in submarine areas. Combining our new and previous seafloor surveying with submersible observations and sampling reveals that vast areas around the northern Hawaiian Islands are covered by rejuvenated lavas. These areas are highly reflective in sidescan sonar images (Holcomb and Robinson, 2004, Garcia et al., 2008) and have yielded young lavas (Table 1; Sherrod et al., 2007, Cousens and Clague, 2015). We estimate that rejuvenation stage lavas cover an area of ∼2400 km2 around Ka‘ula, and ∼4400 km2 on and around the island of Ni‘ihau based on sidescan imagery for both areas (e.g., Holcomb and Robinson, 2004, Garcia et al., 2008), and sampling and geochronology (Greene et al., 2010, Ito et al., 2013, Garcia et al., 2015, Cousens and Clague, 2015). This is much greater than the area of rejuvenated lava estimated for Savai‘i Volcano in the Samoan Islands (∼1700 km2), which was previously considered to have the most extensive deposits of rejuvenated lavas (Konter and Jackson, 2012). The large volume of rejuvenated volcanism on Savaii has been attributed to flexural bending in the nearby Tonga trench (Natland, 1980, Konter and Jackson, 2012). Although flexural uplift from the rapid loading of the lithosphere may contribute to Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism (e.g., Bianco et al., 2005), it alone is unable to explain the large volumes of rejuvenated lavas in the northern Hawaiian Islands (e.g., on Kauai; Garcia et al., 2010).

Radiometric ages of Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas allow the presence and duration of the eruptive hiatus between shield and rejuvenated stages of volcanism to be determined, and to establish the frequency and duration of rejuvenated volcanism (e.g., Gran Canaria, Guillou et al., 2004; Mauritius, Moore et al., 2011). A good geochronological dataset for Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas is now available (Table 1; Ozawa et al., 2005, Greene et al., 2010, Garcia et al., 2010, Garcia et al., 2015). Some surprising features emerge from the recent ages for Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism that challenge existing models for rejuvenated volcanism. All five of the northern Hawaiian shield volcanoes have undergone long-lived (>1 Myr) rejuvenated volcanism (Fig. 3). In contrast, only three of seven extinct southern Hawaiian shields (O‘ahu to Maui) have experienced rejuvenated volcanism and where present, it was short-lived and produced very small volumes in two areas (East Moloka‘i and West Maui; Sherrod et al., 2007). Paradoxically, these southern shields have not as of yet had any rejuvenated volcanism within the last 300 ka (Sherrod et al., 2007), whereas two northern Hawaiian shields (South Kaua‘i Swell and Kaua‘i) have had more recent volcanism (0.08 and 0.15 Ma; Fig. 3). Other northern shields (Ka‘ula and Ni‘ihau) may have had more recent submarine volcanism (based on the lack of sediment cover in side-scan sonar imagery; Garcia et al., 2008) but have not been sampled sufficiently to confirm this suggestion. Rejuvenated volcanism on Ko‘olau volcano (O‘ahu) was more widespread than the other southern shields but much less than on the northern Hawaiian shields, producing ∼40 vents over the last ∼0.7 Myr including many that are less than 0.1 Ma (Ozawa et al., 2005). Given the episodic nature of rejuvenated volcanism (Ozawa et al., 2005, Garcia et al., 2010), it is possible that more volcanism will occur in the future on the other northern Hawaiian shields.

The observed 0.6–2.0 Myr hiatus between shield and rejuvenated volcanic stages (Fig. 3) implies that the underlying shield volcano was transported 60–200 km (assuming recent Pacific plate motion of 100 km/Myr; Garcia et al., 1987, Wessel and Kroenke, 2007) away from the location where the last shield-building eruptions occurred. On the island of Hawai‘i, post-shield eruptions have occurred recently up to 50 km from the vertical mantle plume stem under the island (Sherrod et al., 2007). New ages show that rejuvenated volcanism initiated at widely varying distances away from the plume stem (110–250 km). Other key geochronological observations are: (1) the long distance (500–570 km) from the most recent rejuvenated volcanism on Ka‘ula, Ni‘ihau and Kaua‘i to the locus of maximum loading on the island of Hawaii; and (2) the nearly coeval occurrence from ∼0.3 to 0.6 Ma of rejuvenated volcanism along a 450 km segment of the Hawaiian Islands (West Maui to north of Ni‘ihau). These geochronological observations are inconsistent with predictions of the flexural uplift melting model (Bianco et al., 2005), the secondary melting model (Ribe and Christensen, 1999) and the “underbelly” model (Hofmann and Farnetani, 2013), which all fail to explain the down axis extent of volcanism in the northern Hawaiian Islands. The geodynamic model of Ballmer et al., 2011, Ballmer et al., 2013 simulates the rise of a hot Hawaiian plume containing both peridotite and pyroxenite, and its interaction with small scale convection cells in the 90+ Myr-old oceanic lithosphere under the Hawaiian Islands. This model predicts volcanism will extend up to 520 km downstream of the plume stem. The presence of pyroxenite and small scale convection cells results in an extended duration (up to 520 km downstream of the plume stem) and high volumes of rejuvenated volcanism. Is there evidence for pyroxenite in the source of rejuvenated lavas from Ka‘ula and on other Hawaiian shields?

5.3. Source lithology of Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas

Pyroxenite has been inferred to represent a significant source lithology for Hawaiian rejuvenated lavas based on the relatively high 187Os/188Os isotope values reported for some rejuvenated lavas from Kaua‘i and O‘ahu (Lassiter et al., 2000) and the olivine chemistry in South Kaua‘i Swell lavas (Garcia et al., 2015). The use of olivine composition to determine the presence of pyroxenite in the source was pioneered by Sobolev et al. (2005). The method assumes that quartz-normative melts are generated by partial melting of eclogite from recycled subducted ocean crust, which react with peridotite to form olivine-free pyroxenite. Pyroxenite-derived melts should be enriched in Ni and depleted in Mn, compared to melts generated by peridotite (Sobolev et al., 2005, Sobolev et al., 2007). Thus, the Ni and Mn contents of olivine can be used to determine the original proportions of the contributing parental lithologies for basalts (pyroxenite vs. peridotite; Sobolev et al., 2005, Sobolev et al., 2007, Gurenko et al., 2009, Gurenko et al., 2010). The weight fraction of pyroxenite-derived melt (Xpx) in Ka‘ula lavas was inferred using the equation of Gurenko et al. (2010),(1)Xpx=6.705E-04×(Ni×FeO/MgO)-1.332E-02×(Mn/FeO)+1.5215,where elemental concentrations of Ni and Mn are given in ppm, and FeO and MgO, in wt.%.

Considerable debate has arisen questioning whether high Ni and Fe/Mn in olivine reflect a major pyroxenite contribution (>50%) in the source for Hawaiian basalts (e.g., Herzberg, 2011, Putirka et al., 2011, Rhodes et al., 2012). The high Ni content and Fe/Mn in olivine from Hawaiian tholeiitic lavas can be attributed to high temperatures of melt formation and the difference in temperature between melt segregation and olivine crystallization (e.g., Putirka et al., 2011, Matzen et al., 2013). Elegant experimental work demonstrated that the partition coefficient for Ni in olivine is strongly temperature dependent (Matzen et al., 2013). Thus, when a deep partial melt of a peridotitic mantle source is brought to low pressure and cooled, the early Mg-rich olivines will be Ni-rich. The high Fe/Mn in Hawaiian olivine has also been explained as an outer core signature (Humayun et al., 2004), although partial melts of an olivine-free source, eclogite or a secondary garnet pyroxenite, would also have elevated Fe/Mn (Huang et al., 2007). Another issue is the assumed Ni content of the source: is it low (1900 ppm) as proposed by Sobolev et al. (2005) or higher (2300 ppm), as found by Rhodes et al. (2012) for the mean of mantle peridotite published values? If higher source values are correct, the Ni content of Hawaiian olivine does not require an olivine-free source (Rhodes et al., 2012). High precision studies of Fe/Mn in Hawaiian shield lavas indicate a possible role for pyroxenite in their source but much less than proposed based on olivine composition (10–20% vs. >50%; Sobolev et al., 2005, Sobolev et al., 2007, Huang et al., 2007). The studies noted above advocate for peridotite as the primary source for Hawaiian shield lavas but the results of these studies do not preclude a significant role for pyroxenite. It should be noted that none of these studies examined rejuvenated lavas, which is the focus of this study.

Euhedral olivine phenocrysts (10–12/sample) were analyzed for major and minor elements using high precision methods (see methods section above for details) from 10 lavas (six submarine and four island accidental blocks) that span the compositional range for Ka‘ula lavas (Table 2). The median value of the weight fraction of pyroxenite component (Xpx) in the melts for these Ka‘ula rejuvenated basalts ranges from 33% to 69%, with the island lavas having consistent median values (50.4–54.5%; Table 2). There is no apparent correlation of Xpx with alkalinity, although there is a broad negative correlation of Xpx with Al2O3/CaO for the six submarine lavas (R2 = 0.58) but not if the island samples are included (Table 2). Negative correlations were found for high precision Mn concentrations with total alkali content and Al2O3/CaO in tholeiitic lavas from Hawaiian volcanoes Ko‘olau and Kīlauea (Huang et al., 2007). Ka‘ula lavas show a broad positive correlation for Xpx with the radiogenic Pb isotope ratios (R2 = 0.66; Fig. 14). The correlation remains about the same with the addition of three rejuvenated lavas from nearby South Kaua‘i Swell (SKS) volcano (R2 = 0.64; Fig. 14). If the few shield lavas from SKS and Kauai that we have high precision olivine results and Pb isotopes are included, the correlation improves somewhat (R2 = 0.76; Fig. 14). Thus, there is an apparent significant contribution (>30%) of pyroxenite to magmas from at least some of the northern Hawaiian Island lavas and this component has a distinct Pb isotope signature. A good correlation was found for Mn concentration vs. radiogenic Pb in some Hawaiian shield basalts (Huang et al., 2007). Thus, the source for Hawaiian basalts (rejuvenated and shield lavas) apparently contains variable Mn, which may be a good indicator of its heterogeneity in lithology. The percentage of pyroxenite in the source for these lavas is much less than indicated by the Xpx component in the melts for Ka‘ula lavas (33–69%) because melting in the Hawaiian mantle plume would preferentially tap the mafic component, if it is present as a separate lithology (see discussion by Herzberg, 2011). For SKS lavas, the Xpx in olivine was 68–88%, although only 13–15% mafic crust was estimated for their source based on trace elements (Garcia et al., 2015).

Studies of some Atlantic oceanic island lavas also found correlations in the Xpx values with Pb, Sr and Nd isotope ratios from shield and rejuvenation volcanic stages (e.g., R2 = 0.52–0.62 for Madeira lavas; Gurenko et al., 2013). The correlation of Xpx vs. Pb isotope ratios in Madeira lavas has a positive trend as observed for Ka‘ula and South Kaua‘i Swell lavas. In the Madeira lavas, the Xpx to Pb isotope ratio correlation was attributed to recycled oceanic crust (Gurenko et al., 2010, Gurenko et al., 2013). High radiogenic Pb isotope values are a characteristic feature of the Loa source component in Hawaiian lavas, which is thought to be derived from a large low-shear-velocity province in the deep mantle to the west of Hawai‘i (e.g., Weis et al., 2011) and is probably a recycled crustal component.

6. Conclusions

Marine surveying and rock sampling (mostly with the JASON ROV) was undertaken of Ka‘ula Volcano, located 100 km off the axis of the Hawaiian chain. This westernmost volcano within the main Hawaiian Islands has long been neglected because of its remote and mostly submarine location. Geochemical studies were made on Ka‘ula’s submarine and subaerial rocks using a wide range of methods. The new results show:

  • 1.

    Ka‘ula Volcano is the oldest of the main Hawaiian Islands based on a 40Ar/39Ar age on a tholeiitic accidental block (6.2 Ma) collected from the young cone that forms Ka‘ula Island. The island is surrounded and capped by young volcanic lavas (1.9–0.5 Ma) based on eight new 40Ar/39Ar ages.

  • 2.

    The lavas from Ka‘ula are mostly olivine-phyric with some containing plagioclase and rarely, clinopyroxene. Compositions of these lavas range widely, from foiditic to weakly alkalic basalt, with one tholeiitic accidental block recovered.

  • 3.

    The ages and chemistry of Ka‘ula alkaline rocks overlap with rejuvenated lavas from nearby, northern Hawaiian Island shields (Ni‘ihau, Kaua‘i and South Kaua‘i Swell). Rejuvenated lavas on and around these northern Hawaiian Islands cover a vast area (∼7000 km2), which is much more extensive than any other area of rejuvenated volcanism worldwide.

  • 4.

    Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas range widely in abundances and ratios of incompatible element abundances (e.g., up to 10× for P2O5 and Th at similar degrees of fractionation, 6× variation in La/Yb, and 2–3× variation in ratios of highly incompatible elements) indicating variable degrees of melting of a heterogeneous source. Heavy REE elements in Ka‘ula lavas are pinned at mantle normalized Yb value of 10 ± 1, indicating garnet in the source. The source for Ka‘ula lavas probably also contained phlogopite and Fe–Ti oxides based on wide ranges and decreasing ratios vs. Nb for K/Ce, Rb/La and Ba/La (phlogopite) and positive trend for Zr/Hf (Fe–Ti oxide).

  • 5.

    The new Ka‘ula ages show that rejuvenated volcanism was nearly coeval from ∼0.3 to 0.6 Ma along a 450 km segment of the Hawaiian Islands (West Maui to north of Ka‘ula). These features are inconsistent with most models for rejuvenated volcanism except a geodynamic melting model, which advocates a significant contribution of pyroxenite to rejuvenated magmas. Olivine phenocryst compositions in Ka‘ula rejuvenated lavas indicate a major (33–69%) pyroxenite component in the melts for these lavas. Radiogenic Pb isotope ratios correlate positively with the percent pyroxenite melt component for Ka‘ula and nearby South Kaua‘i lavas, as was reported for some Atlantic oceanic islands. These results provide strong evidence that pyroxenite is an important source component for northern Hawaiian Island and other oceanic island volcanoes. The presence of pyroxenite in the source may have extended the duration and volume of Hawaiian rejuvenated volcanism.

  • The multiple depleted mantle components in the Hawaiian-Emperor chain

    2020, Chemical Geology
    Citation Excerpt :

    Alteration may undermine the total-alkali versus silica (TAS) rock classification by addition of sodium and removal of potassium and silica, erroneously moving tholeiitic basalts into the alkalic field (Hart et al., 1974; Humphris and Thompson, 1978; Garcia et al., 2015). In this study, volcanic stage classification is guided by the TAS rock classification (Fig. 1 inset) and is confirmed with sample distribution relative to defined fields from Hawaiian Island samples on a Zr/Y versus Nb/Y plot, which is less affected by alteration (Fig. 2a) (Fitton et al., 1997; Greene et al., 2010; Garcia et al., 2015), degree of enrichment in trace elements, and isotopic signature as Hawaiian rejuvenated rocks are characterized by depleted isotopic characteristics: low 87Sr/86Sr and high 143Nd/144Nd (Tagami et al., 2003; Frey et al., 2005; Xu et al., 2005, 2007; Fekiacova et al., 2007; Garcia et al., 2010, 2016; Bizimis et al., 2013; Cousens and Clague, 2015). Ages of these samples fall along the linear Hawaiian volcanic age progression array, signifying they are consistent with a Hawaiian-plume related source rather than unrelated tectonism which would likely not fall along this line (Jicha et al., 2018).

  • Osmium isotope evidence for a heterogeneous <sup>3</sup>He/<sup>4</sup>He mantle plume beneath the Juan Fernandez Islands

    2019, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta

  • Unraveling short-lived rejuvenated volcanism and a rapid transition from shield stage at O'Higgins Guyot, Juan Fernández Ridge, Pacific SE

    2018, Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers
    Citation Excerpt :

    Rejuvenated or post-erosional is a common stage in the archetypical evolution of oceanic islands (e.g., Staudigel and Clague, 2010). Magmas related to this period are mostly alkaline isotopically-depleted OIB basalts with a source different (shallower and/or more metasomatized; e.g., Devey et al., 2000) than the deep mantle plume that fed the main shield stage in hotspot volcanoes (French and Romanowicz, 2015; Garcia et al., 2016). This rejuvenated stage usually occurs after a 0.5–2.0 My long quiescence period in fast-moving plates (Garcia et al., 2010), when erosion partially obliterates the former edifice, but exposure can be different in slow-moving plates with an also different geochemical signature (Geldmacher and Hoernle, 2000; Schmidt and Schmincke, 2002; Ramalho et al., 2013) Rejuvenated magmatism is usually a low volume stage (<1% total erupted volume) and as a consequence these rocks are scarce and hard to find even at oceanic islands (except in Samoa, where post-erosional lavas are abundant; e.g., Konter and Jackson, 2012).
